The '''Kilohana Art League''' was formed in 1894 as [[Honolulu]]’s first art association. In May 1894, the woodcarver [[Augusta Graham]], the sculptor [[Allen Hutchinson]], and painters [[D. Howard Hitchcock]] and [[Annie H. Park]] created a forum where local artists could exhibit together and share ideas.<ref>Severson, 2002, pp. XXIV-XXV</ref> Other members included [[Alfred Richard Gurrey, Sr.]]<ref>Severson, 2002, p. 111</ref> and [[Bessie Wheeler]].<ref>[[Thrum's Hawaiian Annual]], Honolulu, Thos. C. Thrum, 1900, p. 122</ref>
“Kilohana’’ is a compound word derived from two [[Hawaiian language]] words: “''kilo''” meaning to observe carefully or to spy out, and “''hana''”, meaning work.<ref>Rodgers, C. T., 1896</ref> The Kilohana Art League was disbanded in 1913, and its funds were transferred to the [[Outdoor Circle]].<ref>Severson, 2002, p. 104</ref>
==References== * Rodgers, C. T., “Kilohana Art League” in ''[[Thrum's Hawaiian Annual|The Hawaiian Annual]]'', 1896, pp.&nbsp;136–140. * Severson, Don R. ''Finding Paradise: Island Art in Private Collections'', University of Hawaii Press, 2002, pp.&nbsp;XXIV-XXV, 99, 104, 111, 210.
